{"author":{"id":"d090680751e9d81548e628ee372337dbb14df0993593a8afe125eaa85e30d5d8"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1628299855,"nonce":"LMe2/SN1R8hhKaqgR/3Aj1Wqw7I=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDOAW4Y0s41UksA","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/3695#issuecomment-894585600"},"message":"@bernt-matthias Just wanted to add my two cents to this conversation.\n\nI am having similar issues developing an interactive tool which takes an `rds` file as an input. It seems that the datatype`rdata` is **not** truly agnostic to whether the source is of `*.rds` or `*.rda` origin:\n\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/42562517/128579551-a7f3c2f9-117e-4ace-a2ef-8682208f58ea.png)\n\nIt could be the first time this has been noticed if users would not usually upload an `rds` file (I imagine it would usually be used for tool output?). And I assume it's just the sniffer returning `False` so not a huge technical issue - but it does suggest that the `rdata` datatype was created for handling `rda` files.\n\nWhile it is still technically possible for me to work with this (I think?), as Mike points out above it is bad for user experience when a tool output is of an \"anonymous\" format. If I download an `rds` file which Galaxy has named `file.rdata`, how am I supposed to know that I should load it with `readRDS()` instead of `load()`?\n\nFurthermore, if I am a inexperienced R user (which I am) then I might not even know that there is a distinction, so when `load()` fails, I would assume that Galaxy rendered a corrupt file:\n\n```\n\u003e obj \u003c- load('file.rdata')\n\nError in load(\"file.rdata\") :\n  bad restore file magic number (file may be corrupted) -- no data loaded\nIn addition: Warning messages:\n1: In readChar(con, 5L, useBytes = TRUE) :\n  truncating string with embedded nuls\n2: file ‘file.rdata’ has magic number 'X'\n  Use of save versions prior to 2 is deprecated\n```\n\nFor the tool I am developing I have chosen to use a composite datatype as that represents the input data most accurately, but for the wider issue I think that a new Galaxy datatype for `rds` would clarify things a lot for users and developers? It would then be beneficial (but not necessary) to update tools with `rds` input/output to utilize this new datatype. And of course, it could be implemented in future tool wraps to make the handling of `rda` and `rds` formats more transparent for everyone.\n\nCurrently we have a confused party of three in our team:\n- Myself (new Galaxy developer)\n- Mike (@mthang, Galaxy tool developer)\n- Sarah (experienced R user and Galaxy end user)\n\nI look forward to hearing your thoughts!","files":null}]}